This Grammar not only presents the latest and best results of Greek studies, but also treats the language in the light received from compar- ative philology. Its comprehensive treatment ol the principles and forms oi the Greek language, together with its clear, analytic method, has made it at once an‘authoritative and exhaustive treatise lor reference, and at the same time a practical and popular text-book for class use. The fact that during all these years it has held its place 'and maintained its widespread popularity and extensive use in the leading classical schools and colleges of the country, without change or revision, isin itself sufficient evidence of the excellence of the original work.

Professor Hadley's Greek Grammar was published in 1860, and was founded on the scholarly and exhaustive Griechische Schulgrammatik of the eminent German scholar and professor, Georg Curtius, of the Uni- versity of Kiel.

Professor Allen brought to the work of revision the enthusiasm and critical method of an accomplished scholar, combined with the experience aud skill of a successful teacher, and the result of his labors is gratifying alilre to the publishers and friends ol the Grammar.

The favor with which the revised edition has been received attests the thoroughness and discretion that characterize the revision.

In its present form it is a practical work for beginners. Clearness of statement, accuracy of definition, and judicious arrangement recom- mend it lor elementary classes; yet at ,the same time it is a complete and comprehensive manual for the advanced student.

Among the chief changes made in the revision are the following: The extension of the parts on moods and tenses; versification and word - formation; the marking of the quantity of the doubtful vowels, and the statement of the source ol all Greek examples given in the Syntax.
